Prosper Loan Data Visualization¶

by Jamal Taghavimehr¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. I will narrow my analysis on 18 variables.

I decide to narrow my analysis to the the completed and charged-off loans from loan status column which are finalized and give a better representation about other variables. This way I can better decide if lower credit score or more delinquencies lead to higher borrower APR.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

Initially there were a total of 113937 entries in the dataset and 81 attributes but I decided to truncate my data to completed loans from loan status variable. This was one of the major categories in this variable and a good subset to create visulas for other variables and derive more solemn conclusions since the loans are not current anymore. The truncated dataset (compchar_loan) had 50066 entries and there was no duplicated values. 18 variables were chosen for analysis in comchar_loan2 in which 6 variables were categorical and 12 were numerical. After dropping null values the dataset (comchar_loan3) had 24978 entries. After testing the dataset several times it looks clean and tidy.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

Borrower APR can be affected by many factors including credit score, prosper score, employment status, income range, and lower range of creadit score. These variables will be tested to investigate their effects on Borrower APR along with other exploratory analysis between other variables.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

High income range, prosper score, credit score all can lead to lower borrower APR due to lower risk of not returning loan to the investors.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Borrower APR has a normal distribution but there is a huge spike at 35% APR while there might be a valid reason for this. So I decided to keep the data as is and also didn't find any outliers or skewness. No data transformation was needed to be done on Borrower APR. I also need to point out that I subset my data to completed and charged-off loans from load status variable before starting my exploratory visualization. I wanted to narrow my analysis to a subset of data with finalized applications which would provide more robust conclusions. This visualization can later continue with current applications too for later.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I inspected a couple of categorical and numerical variables that some of them high skewness. For example, Delinquencies over Last 7 Years showed very high right skewed distribution and I also needed to exclude delinquencies equal to 0 to better inspect the distribution of the variable. Moreover, Total Credit Lines over Past 7 years was right skewed. I performed log transformation of data and it turned into a normal distribution.

Looking at the lower range of APR on the first graph with increasing prosper score the APR reduces in a linear fasion. There is almost no borrower with prosper score of 1 who earned the loan with APR less than 20%. On the other hand, people with prosper score of 10 are drastically reduced in numbers when APR is increased. The same story and trends can be observed from the relation between APR and credit score. No borrower has achieved their loan with APR less than 10% if their credit score has been 600. On the other hand, not a lot of borrowers have achieved their loan with APR higher than 20% if their credit score have been around 850.

As seen earlier borrower APR seems to be at 35% for the majority of borrowers but the boxplot of APR vs Prosper score can give more insights into this. The median of the distribution of borrowers for Prosper score below 5 is kept at 35% while with increase in Prosper score from 5 to 10 the APR starts to decrease drastically and maybe significantly.
